{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"527fe770-deb4-49af-91ab-74cd7d65fcd1","content":"In .NET 10 MAUI, the iOS-specific `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a **cross-platform** `SafeAreaRegions` property on `Page`.\n\n**Before (.NET 9):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\n**After (.NET 10):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             SafeAreaRegions=\"All\">\n    <!-- your content -->\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n`SafeAreaRegions` is a flags enum — you can also use `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, `Right`, or combine them (`Top,Bottom`) if you only need partial insets. Use `All` for the equivalent of the old `UseSafeArea=\"True\"`. You can also remove the `xmlns:ios` namespace if it's no longer needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fa6f57b1-f13e-4f41-9f1d-80903516b568","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a known breaking change in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\nIn .NET 10, the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` attached property was removed/deprecated. The replacement is to use the new `SafeAreaRegions` property that was introduced in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\nLet me provide the correct answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI changes:\n\nIn .NET 10 MAUI, `Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a more granular `Page.SafeAreaRegions` property. \n\nThe new property gives you finer control by letting you specify exactly which regions should respect safe areas—you can target all regions or just specific ones like left, top, right, or bottom. Instead of the old iOS-specific attached property, you'd now set `SafeAreaRegions=\"All\"` directly on the ContentPage to achieve the same effect. In .NET 10, the approach shifts to using a cross-platform `SafeAreaRegions` property directly on the `ContentPage`, which accepts flags like `All`, `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, and `Right` to handle safe areas across both iOS and Android platforms. This replaces the iOS-specific approach and provides more granular control over which regions to respect.","outputTokens":950,"requestId":"D458:5160:1BAE21B:1F36BF4:6A07BFFA"},"id":"c4a2db24-3dfa-4f39-b28c-af2b7ca05d69","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:53:29.633Z","parentId":"faf69f46-de31-4be3-b8c1-83df4a21edd0"}
